rounds.response:
I can see that P1 is simply flipping my own last offer, trying to push it back unchanged.  
A static trading partner at this stage means I should either (1) sweeten the deal so P1 actually accepts, or (2) pivot to a more balanced proposal P1 might realistically want.

Value check on my last rejected offer
- Offered (to P1): 6 Wheat (6 × 6 = 36) + 4 Sheep (4 × 15 = 60) = 96 value  
- Asked (from P1): 5 Brick (5 × 26 = 130) + 1 Ore (1 × 34 = 34) = 164 value  
Net swing of 68 in my favor – clearly too steep for P1 to consider.

Simplest way to make the same skeletal deal acceptable is to leave everything but Brick unchanged and cut back on how many Bricks I demand.

New offer
[Offer: 6 Wheat, 4 Sheep -> 3 Brick, 1 Ore]

So far, every offer either way has been turned down, and the game is now beyond the midway point.  
For this round (turn 7) I want to offer Player 1 something that is a little more appealing than my previous proposals while still improving the overall value of my hand.

Current totals and unit-values (just to keep them in mind):

- Wheat  19 × 6  = 114  
- Wood  9 × 12 = 108  
- Sheep  17 × 15 = 255  
- Brick  12 × 26 = 312  
- Ore  24 × 34 = 816  

My cheapest resources (per-unit value) are Wheat and Wood.  Player 1 seems to value Brick and Ore most, because in every one of their counter-offers they asked for exactly those two.  To get any movement at all, the simplest thing is to offer them what they want but at a mild surplus in my favor over the last refused numbers.

I am willing to give up more Wood and Wheat (the cheap stuff) and ask in return primarily for Brick, which I have already identified as a valuable trading chip.

[Offer: 7 Wheat, 5 Wood, 3 Sheep → 8 Brick, 1 Ore]
